However, the spherical CaCO3 particles basically disappeared and became large aggregates when the ACDs concentration was 0.8 mg/mL. Meanwhile, there may be some small spherical particles in these aggregates. It could be seen from the partially enlarged view of Fig. 3E that this CaCO3 aggregate was formed by the aggregation of nano-scale irregular small particles with a size of about 60 nm. As shown in Fig. S4, N2 adsorption/ desorption of ACC aggregate was carried out. The specific surface area and average pore diameter of ACC aggregate were 88.52 m2/g and 3.65 nm, respectively. At the same time, ACC aggregate presented the H1 hysteresis loops and typical IV-type isotherm, which was the feature of the mesoporous materials [33]. These CaCO3 aggregates were identified by FTIR and XRD as ACC (Fig. 4I E and II D). The characteristic peaks of ACC at 866 cm−1 and 1421 cm−1 were due to the υ2 mode and υ1 mode of CO3
                        2– (Fig. 4I E) [34–36]. The XRD pattern of ACC in Fig. 4II D showed no diffraction peak, which indicated that the sample is not crystalline [37,38]. Therefore, the ACC aggregate resulted from the simple aggregation of nucleation clusters. Furthermore, when the concentration of ACDs was 1.0 mg/mL, The CaCO3 was basically irregular aggregates (Fig. 3F). Meanwhile, it can be seen from Fig. 4I F and II F that this CaCO3 aggregate was also ACC. So, ACDs could be used to control the crystal form and morphology (Table 1
                        ) of CaCO3. At low concentrations, calcite spherical CaCO3 particles formed. At high concentrations, ACC could be obtained.
